3ï¸âƒ£ Logic flaws â€“ the most dangerous lesson from Day 15
What logic flaws are

Logic flaws happen when:

The application does what it was programmed to do

But the business rules are wrong or incomplete

No hacking tools requiredâ€”just thinking like an attacker.

Examples of logic mistakes Juice Shop teaches (conceptually)

Trusting client-side values (price, quantity, role)

Allowing actions in the wrong order

Missing checks like â€œShould this user be allowed to do this?â€

Assuming users will behave honestly

Why this is critical

Logic flaws:

Bypass security controls

Are hard to detect with scanners

Often survive code reviews

Cause huge financial and data losses

ğŸ’¡ Big lesson:
Security is not only about code syntaxâ€”itâ€™s about correct decision-making logic.

4ï¸âƒ£ Insecure authentication â€“ how identity systems fail

Juice Shop strongly reinforces that authentication is more than login forms.

What insecure authentication looks like

Weak password rules

Predictable or poorly protected credentials

No rate limiting

Insecure password reset logic

Tokens or sessions not properly validated

Why modern apps fail here

Developers rely too much on frameworks

Misunderstanding how sessions/tokens work

Assuming authentication libraries are â€œsecure by defaultâ€

Poor handling of error messages and edge cases

Real-world impact

Account takeover

Privilege escalation

Data exposure

Admin access without authorization

ğŸ‘‰ Juice Shop shows that identity is the first and most critical security boundary.

5ï¸âƒ£ Improper validation â€“ trusting the wrong side
What improper validation means

Validation is often:

Done only on the client side

Inconsistent across APIs

Missing for edge cases

Focused on format, not intent

Juice Shop teaches this key rule:

Never trust the client. Ever.

Modern apps:

Use APIs

Exchange JSON data

Depend on frontend frameworks

Attackers donâ€™t use the UIâ€”they talk directly to the backend.

Common validation failures Juice Shop highlights

Accepting manipulated values

Missing server-side checks

Allowing unexpected input structures

Failing to enforce limits and constraints

Real-world consequences

Unauthorized actions

Data manipulation

Broken workflows

Business rule bypass

